By writing solve(a == L, u, bc) in the program, a linear system will be formed from a and L, and this system is solved for the U1, . . . , UN values. The U1, . . . , UN values are known as degrees of freedom of u. For Lagrange elements (and many other element types) Uk is simply the value of u at the node with global number k. (The nodes and cell vertices coincide for linear Lagrange elements, while for higher-order elements there may be additional nodes at the facets and in the interior of cells.)
Having u represented as a Function object, we can either evaluate u(x) at any vertex x in the mesh, or we can grab all the values Uj directly by

u_nodal_values = u.vector()

