Python code

That is, we manipulate u_array as desired, and then we insert this array into u’s Vector object. The
/= operator implies an in-place modiﬁcation of the object on the left-hand side: all elements of the u_array are divided by the value max_u. Alternatively, one could write u_array = u_array/max_u,
which implies creating a new array on the right-hand side and assigning this array to the name u_array.
A call like u.vector().array() returns a copy of the data in u.vector(). One must therefore
never perform assignments like u.vector.array()[:] = ..., but instead extract the numpy array (that is, a copy), manipulate it, and insert it back with u.vector()[:] = or u.set_local(...).
