bc.apply(A, b)

Python code

There is an alternative function assemble_system, which can assemble the system and take boundary conditions into account in one call:

A, b = assemble_system(a, L, bcs)

Python code

The assemble_system function incorporates the boundary conditions in the element matrices and vectors, prior to assembly. The conditions are also incorporated in a symmetric way to preserve eventual symmetry of the coefﬁcient matrix. With bc.apply(A,b) the matrix A is modiﬁed in an unsymmetric way.
Note that the solution u is, as before, a Function object. The degrees of freedom, U = A−1b, are ﬁlled into u’s Vector object (u.vector()) by the solve function.
The object A is of type Matrix, while b and u.vector() are of type Vector. We may convert the matrix and vector data to numpy arrays by calling the array() method as shown before. If you wonder how essential boundary conditions are incorporated in the linear system, you can print out A and b

