1.3.2 Implementation

Our program needs to perform the time stepping explicitly, but can rely on FEniCS to easily compute a0, L0, a, and L, and solve the linear systems for the unknowns. We realize that a does not depend on time, which means that its associated matrix also will be time independent. Therefore, it is wise to explicitly create matrices and vectors as in Section 1.1.15. The matrix A arising from a can be computed prior to the time stepping, so that we only need to compute the right-hand side b, corresponding to L, in each pass in the time loop. Let us express the solution procedure in algorithmic form, writing u for the unknown spatial function at the new time level (uk) and u1 for the spatial solution at one earlier time level (uk−1):

