1.3.3 Avoiding assembly
The purpose of this section is to present a technique for speeding up FEniCS simulators for timedependent problems where it is possible to perform all assembly operations prior to the time loop. There are two costly operations in the time loop: assembly of the right-hand side b and solution of the linear system via the solve call. The assembly process involves work proportional to the number of degrees of freedom N, while the solve operation has a work estimate of O(Nα), for some α 1. As N → ∞, the solve operation will dominate for α > 1, but for the values of N typically used on smaller computers, the assembly step may still represent a considerable part of the total work at each time level. Avoiding repeated assembly can therefore contribute to a signiﬁcant speed-up of a ﬁnite element code in time-dependent problems.

